<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-511-790  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 511 790.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Trading places: stock exchanges seek safety nets. (disasterplanning at major stock exchanges)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The American and New York Stock Exchanges are cooperating toprovide disaster recovery and data security services through theirjointly-owned Securities Industry Automation Corp (SIAC)subsidiary.andP;  SIAC is dividing its computer power between two sitesand will implement approximately 15 Tandem Computers Incm fault-tolerant systems and one IBM 3090 mainframe at eachlocation.andP;  It is in the process of migrating NYSE's stock-floorreporting system to an Ungermann-Bass Inc. LAN using the OSIstandard, dual fiber-optic cable, and Ethernet links.andP;  The newEthernet connections will let the SIAC interconnect both NYSE andAmerican Stock Exchange LANs with its own network over multiplestandard T1 interfaces.andP;  Both Tandem and Ungermann-Bass provideOSI support for SIAC that is not yet available on the commercialmarket.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Disaster PlanningRedundancyStock MarketSecurities TransferData Security.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>